To counteract this trend, we initiated the Carpool Challenge Week in March, a special blitz campaign aimed at reinvigorating the initiative, which did result in an increase in log submissions for that month. Thus, one of the challenges we faced was how to maintain project momentum in the face of a natural decrease in engagement, as well as the specific issues of holiday and semester breaks in higher education.

Another challenge for this project (or any alternative commuting project) is that people enjoy the freedom, independence, and flexibility of driving their cars, which is deeply rooted in our culture. Therefore, it is crucial to provide incentives for engaging in alternative commuting methods. We offered many prizes in the form of gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, independent bookstores, and even some larger national chain stores. It would have been interesting to see how larger prizes might have affected participation, such as giving away a nice bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car. This could have also helped combat the dip in engagement experienced during the project. The nature of the prizes did not change much during the course of the project. However, if the value of the prizes increased over time, it might have helped. The gift cards seemed more than adequate at the project's outset, but if we had announced in December the addition of a couple of bicycles and then in January the addition of a hybrid or electric car, one can only imagine that participation and engagement would have increased rather than decreased.

While browsing through the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I chose to watch all the trick films, which totaled fifteen between 1895 and 1901. These films often use creative editing to create illusions. My film study mainly focused on describing the poetics of most trick films and examining unique evolutionary features in some later ones. Generally, the trick films of the turn of the century are confined to a fixed set, composed within a frontal stage frame, feature no camera movement, utilize long and medium shots, and adhere to a strict one shot equals one film methodology. However, some films at the beginning of the twentieth century dared to break these guidelines by introducing elements like multiple shots.

One of the most noticeable common aspects of these trick films is their shooting on an interior set within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera remains stationary and does not follow figures or objects. This composition was very common in early films, drawing its roots from theater and, for trick films, from vaudeville and magic acts. One inherent limitation of using the stage is that figures in trick films generally move only side-to-side, not towards or away from the camera. For instance, in "Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel" (1900), actors enter from the right and move along the horizontal axis. Even when they leave the frame, the camera does not follow.

The frontal proscenium style of composition also results in shots typically being long shots, and less commonly, medium shots. Close-ups are never used in any of the trick films in the Edison catalog. This approach takes after theater and vaudeville traditions, where the audience would view the entire performance at any given time, framed by the stage borders. As with most early films, actors do not move from the middle ground towards the camera, so close-ups do not occur.

Typically, most early trick films follow the pattern where one conceptual shot equals a film. This limits the length of most trick films to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. It also limits the dramatic or narrative use of trick films; most focus on short vaudeville-style tricks, such as magic, disappearing, and switching acts, with little story. However, note that in a trick film, one conceptual shot in the viewer's eyes does not actually equal one physical shot. A single "shot" might actually be several joined together to create the illusion of appearance or disappearance. Take a closer look at "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots" (1895), one of the earlier trick films. A more thorough inspection reveals the moment when the physical shot with Mary's severed "head" begins, even though to the viewer, the whole film conceptually appears as a single shot.

The traditional Gothic Novel, as Ian Watt describes in The Rise of the Gothic Novel, is an "oxymoron for 'Old-New.'" The Gothic style has faced criticism, praise, accusations of lacking depth, and admiration for its 'terrible sublime' aspect (Burke). Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, the original Gothic Novel, combined elements of "ancient and modern" romances to create the proto-Gothic genre and a new form of literary expression. Walpole used "old" theatrical elements and 'new' nature imitations in 'modern' novels to present what he termed "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre draws from medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. Even at the time of The Castle of Otranto's publication, "gothic" was used to describe various styles, peoples, and eras, often viewed as outdated or unsophisticated compared to "modern" societal and literary "advancements." The combination of theatrical "Gothic" and the novel's new format (offering a personal view of characters' psychology) allows the Gothic to endure, both obsolete and new to readers distant in time from its original creation.

Chivalry is one of the most prominent gothic ideas in Gothic novels. The medieval concept of chivalry, the knight-training process, is both preserved and transformed in The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry is significant to Gothic writers because it represents the classic knight—brave, honorable, competent—and the perceived absence of such ideals in society, particularly observed by Walpole. Through chivalric concepts and manners, the "gothic past" becomes idealized and romanticized, hinting at Gothic's evolution into Romantic, and attempts to improve the present. Walpole, when writing The Castle of Otranto, was amid political turmoil and despaired about the future. Immersed in politics and (arguably) unjust accusations, he may have begun to think, even if not explicitly, that the supposed morality and inherent "goodness" of the gothic era had been lost in contemporary society. This concept is apparent in several characters, such as Frederic. Before meeting Frederic, the reader knows he embodies many chivalric traits; he is described as:

The depiction includes many traditional chivalric images; Frederic is primarily a prince, who has suffered, been deeply affected by tragedy, and is believed to have been killed by infidels. The figure of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is exaggerated, introducing the Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management involves the processes of moving goods from customer orders through the stages of raw materials, supply, production, and distribution to the customer. The term was coined by consultant Keith Oliver in 1982. He described the overall process of planning, implementing, and controlling activities within the supply chain to efficiently meet customer needs. There are six key elements in a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers leverage these elements to deliver optimal customer service.

Production, the first step in the supply chain, is the foundation of the entire process. It outlines when, why, where, and how everything will be produced. Managers need to understand customer desires, which can be gauged by examining the market—the primary indicator of customer demand. After analyzing the market, managers decide what and how many products to produce. Once decisions are made, they choose where production should occur and select the best facility for volume and quality, ensuring customer needs and satisfaction are met. After determining the production location, managers focus on scheduling workloads and equipment maintenance. Production is crucial in the supply chain, with every detail being vital. Poor planning can cost the company significant time and money in the long term. For example, when I worked at Wal-Mart and Target, both companies had designs, manuals, and processes for every aspect of the business, from employee uniforms to receiving shipments from trucks. These outlined processes enable smooth operations without confusion about directions and expectations.

The second key element in supply chain management is supply, which involves strategic decisions to determine a facility's core capabilities and develop outsourcing partnerships. A company may have various production divisions for a single product, each with different equipment, workers, and specialties. Managers must decide which division is best suited for different product processes. Management might also outsource work to other companies to create velocity, which is the ability to provide quality and flexibility while reducing costs or maintaining low cost levels.

Victorian novels are known for their meticulous detail and focus on the aristocracy of their time. However, two novels, "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights," deviate from this tradition. These novels incorporate elements of mystery and the bizarre, which are atypical of the period, enhancing the characters and providing deep insights into their motivations and emotions.

At one point, a flood of bewildering and confusing thoughts crowded his mind. He seemed to be walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were arguing angrily, for their words echoed in his ears; when he became aware of himself, he found he was speaking to them. Suddenly, he was jolted by the sound of gunfire, loud cries and shouts filled the air; lights flashed before his eyes, and everything was noise and chaos as if an unseen hand hurriedly whisked him away. Through these rapid visions, there was an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain that continuously tormented him. (Dickens, 220)

These two novels often use mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, with varying content and function in each case. In "Oliver Twist," these strange happenings often reveal insights into Oliver's inner layers, his pains, and his awareness of the true nature of the events around him. When the shooting of Oliver is revisited in chapter 28, he vividly relives the event as if in a dream while struggling to find help. This passage highlights Oliver's lack of control over the events that unfolded and his dire health, strongly presented through his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting overwhelms him, numbing his senses, as he does not notice the "unseen hand" that carries him away; he re-experiences his despair, now linked with fear rather than the shock of pain. With Oliver overwhelmed, the question arises about whose will caused his misfortune, as it certainly wasn't his own. This shooting reinforces the notion that Oliver has little control over anything, unable to even attempt to influence the outcome of events, even when his life is at risk. A growing sense of defeat is also implied, as if old Fagin had begun to break him, forcing him to accept this despair and affecting his ability to respond. Otherwise, it can be assumed Oliver would have made some effort, at least for his own life's sake.

"The day passed – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as it came – and night came again; night so long, yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting hours."

A few years ago, I worked at an after-school program tutoring elementary school students. I tried my best to assist them with any subjects they found challenging, though my expertise was in English and reading. One instructor asked me to help a boy named Adrian (I believe he was in third or fourth grade), who struggled significantly with reading. I realized something was amiss; his difficulties were quite unusual. Some letters he could pronounce perfectly, while others were completely off—it was very strange. He was of Latino descent, I was sure, but the boy spoke fluent English. We kept at it until I met his mother. I was helping watch a few kids (for lack of a better word) while the rest of the after-school group went on a field trip when his mother came in. She didn't speak any English, only Spanish. With my very limited Spanish (as I was just starting to learn), we managed to communicate. It struck me at that moment: Adrian could read just fine; he simply wasn’t familiar with the English alphabet. I’m not sure how much this realization helped him, but I hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to spotlight the issue of language barriers in schools, especially here in California. It also illustrates that these issues aren’t always as apparent as we might think. Even for a child who speaks fluent English, reading can be a significant obstacle. I believe everyone recognizes this problem exists, so what should we do? In Adrian's case, the solution was straightforward: tutoring in English reading, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciations. However, for many children who barely speak English, the solution is far more intricate. There isn’t a single answer. Combining dual language systems, mainstream immersion, private tutors, and ESL classes is essential because none of these alone will solve the problem.

To begin with, the dual language system is an excellent idea. It's beneficial not only for children whose first language is Spanish but for all children. "Children in two-way bilingual education programs have been found to outperform their peers academically." There is a lot of concern about this idea, suggesting it's a waste of resources and the majority of schoolchildren won't benefit. But that's incorrect. If we made these programs the norm rather than the exception, all children would benefit. How do we implement this? Should all teachers be bilingual? No, that's unreasonable and slightly unrealistic. However, I believe there’s no reason we can't have special aides, tutors, or whatever you want to call them, who are bilingual.

From childhood, most of us are told about something greater than ourselves, beyond our comprehension. Some attend Sunday school to learn about it, others go to temples or search within for answers. Many readily accept the religions passed down by our parents, while some reject them, denying anything beyond personal understanding. We might adopt one value system only to later change to another. No matter the path, we strive to define ourselves through our unique spiritual perspectives, searching for a light to guide us from shadows into the sunlight.

"A cardinal," my father said when I asked him his favorite bird. We sat on our porch, listening to the rain hit the tin roof as we smoked together. The rainwater overflowed the gutters, drowning the plants at the porch's edge. He gazed into the rain, a look half searching, half remembering. He had grown thinner recently, his clothes hung loosely, his hair sparser. He continued staring into the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt alone, scared, unable to tell him how much I'd miss him, as speaking would make it all too real. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair closer, and joined him in watching the June twilight rain.

My father passed away that December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemo and radiation did not ease his suffering, only prolonged it beyond doctors' predictions; I couldn't define the value in extending his pain. What kind of God would allow this, I wondered. Alone at night, I offered no prayers. If God existed, I felt he had long stopped listening to me.

I didn't want to see him transition from this life to another, so I didn't. I couldn't watch the life that created me come to an end. I wanted to remember him for how he lived, not how he died. Besides, I knew him better than they did, better than his family, and he wouldn't want his only child to witness his death. I curled up in bed for three days, waiting for the news.

No one called me.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and passionate advocate of Republicanism. Though mainly an agriculturist, his career and brief political involvement made him known for his dedication and outspoken views on personal freedom and government. His commitment to an agrarian system was the foundation for nearly all his government opinions, as he sought to preserve and encourage what he deemed the most superior profession, influencing his arguments on sovereignty, constitutionality, and the judicial system.

John Taylor believed the United States had a significant opportunity to create an ideal system, as there was no native tradition to hinder the government's founders, allowing for the establishment of self-governance. He strongly believed in the natural rights of man, asserting that these rights were interdependent. If one is denied, all would fail, reducing the value of the remaining ones. These rights should, therefore, be beyond the reach of government. He claimed that what some referred to as the "state of nature" meant those with physical strength and malevolent intelligence thrived, but in civilization, this should not be the case.

To create this ideal society, Taylor believed a government must be established that accounts for the inherent good and evil within man. Taylor was very rigid in his views on dualistic morality. He stated that "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human." He defined good principles as those that protect private property, improve agriculture, and discourage capitalism, believing that a government founded on good principles would function fairly, regardless of its administration, which would inevitably be led by greed and self-interest. He considered self-interest man's motivation in all things but saw it as evil only when it surpassed creating a society based on public good to sub-societies thriving at others' expense. A good government was necessary to restrain man's natural evil, and it needed careful observation to avoid introducing harmful principles.

Like many staunch Republicans of his time, Taylor called for a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He wanted an extremely limited Federal government, with no more rights or powers than explicitly stated in the Constitution. He recognized that an extensive Federal government was costly and likely despotic. However, he believed a simple, literal interpretation was risky and could easily become corrupt without considering the writers' intent. Additionally, he regarded the Declaration of Independence as the true charter of the United States, as it more explicitly described the nation as a group of sovereign states rather than a single entity.

I gazed downward, my mind blank as it tried to process the scene before me. Unemotional and silent, I observed with a practiced awareness, deliberately avoiding any abstract interpretations. Thoughts flitted through my mind, appearing and disappearing almost instantly. My consciousness flowed so smoothly that it seemed I had no real thoughts, only an active and fluid experience of what I observed.

Once, following advice from an artist I collaborated with, I bought an art instruction book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." I've wanted to learn to draw since I was six, and this book teaches everything from understanding a pencil to how the brain interprets lines. One technique it teaches is framing an image to make it manageable—transforming an overwhelmingly detailed scene, like a bowl of fruit in a kitchen connected to a dining room, into a simple image of the fruit bowl.

At that moment, staring at the bowl in front of me, I couldn't mentally frame it as an artist might. I was so overwhelmed that I could only stand and gaze in awe. Picasso had his Blue Period, Monet loved greenery, and Italian Renaissance masters displayed a spectrum of colors. If I had any aspirations of seeing my perspective as Artistic, then before me lay the beginnings of my work: "Work in Brown."

Fingertips touched my chosen artistic tool, muscles tensed and relaxed as my hand moved through space, shaping what might have been the most creative moment of my life. Water swirled, serene and clear. Flakes of matter broke away, carried to oblivion. The second time, muscles tightened more, jerking and spasming, as my hand hit the toilet handle again. The stubborn brown package refused to budge, stuck like a slug at the bottom.

Holding a mop loosely, feet apart, a green tie awkwardly knotted at my throat, I frowned at the rude bundle of processed matter left as a message for those who clean the bathrooms at Rite Aid. After a few more flushes and moments of quiet introspection, my hand moved to the wall, grabbed the toilet paper, and wrapped itself into a makeshift mitt. Standing upright, then bending at the waist, my hand slowly dipped into the bowl, like a mother reaching into the oven for the Thanksgiving turkey...

Teenagers are dying in car accidents. Many factors combine to create this deadly statistic for the youngest American drivers. The National Institutes of Health point out that one aspect of the issue is that the teenage brain is not yet prepared for the dangers of driving. Inexperience is also at the heart of the problem. This lack of experience not only leads to more fatal accidents but also results in higher rates of vehicle rollovers, speeding, and running off the road.  
When teens travel with peers, the situation worsens—something anyone with common sense knows happens regularly. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center conducted a study showing a correlation between the age of passengers and the number of traffic accidents.  
California and other states have tried to enhance teen driver safety by requiring temporary licenses that limit driving hours and prohibit other minors as passengers.  
However, in my opinion, provisional licenses are merely stopgap measures. The real issue is that, as a group, the youngest drivers, by all statistical measures, cannot adequately handle the risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes that even 18 is too young for a regular driver's license. USA Today reports that Zuckerman's research suggests that those under 19-20 have a common desire to take risks merely for the thrill. Thus, it makes sense to delay driving until this thrill-seeking tendency begins to stabilize. If we continue issuing licenses to young teens, not only will fatal accidents continue, but death tolls might reach staggering levels in the coming years. By 2010, the children of the Baby Boomers will be eligible to drive, and millions of new teen drivers will be ready to hit the road.  
Legislation addressing this issue should be relatively straightforward. Schools could continue to offer driver's education classes to start the learning process for future drivers, but no one under 18 should operate a motor vehicle. A temporary permit could still be issued before granting a full license, requiring a certain number of practical training hours. The required hours could be based on the number already mandated by most states (for example, California currently requires 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult). Since deadly statistics for teen drivers come from across all states, national legislation on this issue would be a reasonable—and I believe effective—way to protect teens nationwide.  
The legislation I propose is by no means a novel idea.

This paper discusses three aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, it provides a brief definition of the disorder. Then, it explains the diagnosis process, highlighting common characteristics or "red flags." Finally, the paper concludes with ways a teacher in a mainstream classroom can support a student with CAPD.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), refers to how efficiently and effectively the central nervous system (CNS) uses auditory information. In a narrower sense, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiological activities underlying that processing, which create electrophysiological auditory potentials (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This means it is a disorder where the central nervous system (i.e., the brain) cannot properly process what is heard. People with CAPD can hear normally and are not considered "hearing impaired"; instead, the part of the brain that translates what we hear, separating words or distinguishing conversation from background noise, does not function as it typically should.

The earliest reference to what became known as CAPD was in the mid-1950s, called "auditory imperception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), when researchers were evaluating children with communication disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari started developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura "introduced dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the Central Auditory Nervous System (CANS) underlying dichotic perception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference in 1977 spurred further research on children with CAPD.

CAPD presents itself in various ways: a person may be unable to localize or hear sounds in space; may struggle to distinguish between two or more "acoustic events" (sound occurrences); may not recognize sound patterns; may not differentiate changes in speech (like detecting sarcasm based on voice changes); one sound may be masked by a subsequent sound; may lack the ability to synthesize auditory clues (that is, interpret them in a meaningful way to take action); and may not determine the sequence of auditory information presentation (Ferre).

To diagnose CAPD, the patient must undergo "systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function," which may be conducted by "audiologists, speech-language pathologists (SLPs), psychologists, and others using various measures to evaluate auditory-related skills" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires, surveys, and observation of auditory behaviors, including how the patient responds to certain stimuli. Currently, there is no single tool or test consistently used for a high rate of diagnostic success, and there is no known cause for the disorder. Many tests present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and ask them to differentiate certain items, such as a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests involve recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring responses to the signals.

In my pursuit of an education in social work, I aim to build a career with the Division of Family and Children Services to assist children who have suffered abuse or neglect and to support families in distress. The values I bring to social work include service, respect, ethical integrity, a commitment to improving relationships among people, and a dedication to enhancing my professional skills to remain competent in my field. These core values are significant not only to social workers but also to me personally.

I have always wanted to help others, though I was uncertain about the career path I should take. During my high school and college years, I observed many individuals denying their problems and a few adopting less than ideal coping mechanisms. Witnessing these situations led me to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still unsure about my career path, I took a break after graduating from Piedmont College in 2009. One summer day, I visited a friend who introduced me to a nervous sixteen-year-old boy on her couch. She explained he was there to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned he had called the police to his parents' home. To see if I could help, I drove to his parents’ house and privately expressed my concerns to the police, mentioning my recent degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police asked me to speak with the parents, as the law could do nothing for the teenager. When I questioned the parents, they appeared anxious and made excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior in involving outsiders to resolve “simple” disputes. This experience prompted me to seriously consider a career in social work to assist children with “simple” family disputes.

Another key value for social work is social justice. As a society, we claim individuals matter and mourn those we lose. However, society's concept of the “individual” seems more like a follower of outdated traditions than true uniqueness. If society mourns lost individuals, why do we strive to be like “everyone else?” I am an individual and dislike limiting myself to conform to others. Throughout my high school and college years, I protested against social injustice whenever possible: dyeing my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothes that reflected my personality, piercing my ears beyond traditional settings, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), and fighting against racism and discrimination whenever I saw it. I believe in social justice and will continue to stand against social injustice.

The paper explores the biological and sociocultural models related to insomnia. The biological model emphasizes genetic information and medical health aspects, while the sociocultural model examines environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. This review of insomnia analyzes these models, explaining each selected study's relevance and contribution to understanding these models. The research explanations and findings are critiqued to highlight specific strengths and weaknesses.

Sleep disorders can be classified as primary sleep disorders, those related to another mental disorder, or linked to other issues. Primary sleep disorders include Dyssomnias or Parasomnias, while those related to another mental disorder are associated with Axis I or Axis II disorders. Other categories of sleep disorders may arise from medical complications or substance intake. Dyssomnias include Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). Primary Insomnia involves difficulties in obtaining or maintaining adequate sleep, while Primary Hypersomnia involves difficulty staying awake for at least a month. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/or automatic REM. While Dyssomnias focus on sleep initiation and maintenance, Parasomnias are linked to behavioral abnormalities and/or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. Sleep disorders related to other mental disorders involve difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). This review focuses on insomnia and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in relation to biological and sociocultural models.

The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspects. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin regulate sleep and wakefulness. This study involved experiments with mice and found phenotypic GABAB receptors on orexin neurons responsible for sleep/wake states. Activation of the GABAA receptor promotes sleep, and inhibiting its firing can reduce anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). These findings suggest that mouse models can be generalized to human studies, showing a genetic and environmental basis for the GABAB receptor in humans. Problems or deficiencies with this receptor may affect one's ability to achieve adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication is that if this phenotype is inherited, it could regulate sleep, and receptor alterations might naturally disturb an individual's sleep. This would negatively impact life aspects such as school, career, and daily activities requiring focus.

I have been a student at University Park for about two and a half years, which equates to four and a half semesters. For many, myself included, navigating campus can present challenges. During my freshman year, I was housed in East Halls, nearly the easternmost point of the campus, excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in distant locations like the Willard building, near the campus center, could take up to 25 minutes, especially in the frequently adverse weather of State College. In conversation with a slightly older alum, I discovered that not long ago, the East Halls dorms were isolated from the rest of the school by vast tracts of unused land. Today, that space is filled with sports fields, large new buildings like the new Creamery and health services building, and is surrounded by apartments. As the campus continues to grow, moving from one place to another becomes increasingly difficult. What is the best solution to mobility issues? On a college campus, it's the bicycle. However, bikes alone won't resolve any issues. Students must use them, and the campus should be designed to accommodate cyclists' needs.

I spoke with a friend who recently resumed cycling after a hiatus of several years. He remarked on how he wondered why he ever stopped. "Bikes are great," he said, "for a few years, biking wasn't cool, but it's the only way to get around." Besides being good for your body, cycling is the most efficient mode of travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a bit of physical effort can carry you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off-campus, just as far from the campus center as some dorms. The smartest decision I made this year was purchasing a bike. I have classes daily in the Thomas building, which is easily a 25-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can reduce that time to 5 minutes if I pedal quickly. The only issue is that Pollock Road is the most direct route to the Thomas building from my house, and it's not always easy to travel, with or without a bike. Walking has its merits too, but personally, I'm too busy for it. Without my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas daily would take an extra 30-40 minutes of my day, totaling over two and a half hours each week. Add to that all the other time I'd spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and so on. That's more time than I can afford.

Aldous Huxley, in his novel Brave New World, critiques the looming threat of technology and the capitalist structure that reinforces it by creating a dystopian world. The society in the novel values the community over the individual and is conditioned from the start to seek immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are shown as pawns in a larger scheme, bound to a single ideology dictated by the World Controller. Through the lens of Marxist theism, one can see the author's underlying skepticism regarding the development of these systems. Common Marxist terms like homogeny and reification reinforce the idea that Huxley’s novel comments on the flaws of the emerging economy of his time. Capitalism is satirized using the Marxist concept of false consciousness. Essentially, ordinary citizens are prevented from understanding true economic relations with other classes because they are primarily interested in their own gain. This is seen as a result of ideological control over the proletariat and common workers, something quite evident in the conditioning of people in Brave New World. The common classes, such as Delta and Gamma, have no true will of their own; through hypnopaedia, the drive to consume, spend, and indulge is reinforced above all else. As previously mentioned, this is manipulated by the World Controller. Hegemony, essentially the idea that social class groups are completely dominated by a separate group of individuals, is obviously employed here. The lower classes are entirely unaware of this manipulation, quite literally 'buying into an ideology that supports that structure' (i.e., capitalism and consumerism). The upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing; few Alphas or Betas, beyond characters like Bernard, do much more than similarly accept their place. In fact, the interactions of social classes, as will be discussed in greater detail, are significant indicators of the perceived oppression of capitalism.

In Brave New World, relationships between different individuals do not exist. The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters—even major characters lack depth. Perhaps Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprives humanity of free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any emotion; instead, interactions remain superficial, distinctly portrayed through the male characters' comments about women primarily regarding their physical appearance (i.e., pneumatic quality) and the females' unashamed comments about their experiences. Moreover, each societal class's complacency with their status in the hierarchy indicates the socioeconomic effects of capitalism. Their absolute obedience to their role in the community reflects Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely assured of their own superiority so long as they continue to consume, obey, and align with their peers.

About four years ago, I took a course on Islam at CBC. A major heated topic in the class was whether Islam is a hostile religion. I believe this question is more relevant today than ever. Reflecting on events since 9/11, I've seen the media shift from a hostile view of Islam and extremists to extreme tolerance for Islam in America. I don't think in 2001 we could have had a presidential candidate named Barack Obama, with a clear Muslim background in his family.

The biography of the Prophet interests me because, from what I know of Muhammad's history, it contradicts his character. From what I learned, I thought Muhammad forced conversions to Islam, conquering tribes and making them embrace the religion. However, the biography portrays him as a martyr, misunderstood and humble, with people gradually recognizing the 'truth' in his teachings and seeking him out.

There are also striking similarities between the ministries of Jesus and Muhammad's 'miracles'. Notably, he multiplied mutton and milk to feed forty men. This writing style suggests the authors wanted Muhammad seen as a humble prophet, living in truth and miracles without needing to prove anything. This fallacy is troubling because it diminishes the miracles and life of Jesus Christ. It feels like they are borrowing from Jesus' life and essence through Muhammad.

The biography contains many stories suggesting an agenda to provide 'witness' or show how people 'independently' converted to Islam. However, many stories are from third-party perspectives, with the author noting hearsay from various sources. I didn't like this as, although intended to prove the stories' truth, it seemed to weaken them and make them more suspicious.

What bothers me most about this work is the attempt to elevate Muhammad as a godly man who was humble, endearing, wise, and gentle. History contradicts the idea of Muhammad as gentle and humble, and I can't help but wonder if Muslims today know the true history of Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus and his beliefs during his lifetime were quickly left behind as Christian thought progressed after his death. Observing this history broadly, we notice a trend of Christianity diverging further from its origins. Today's world seems to reflect an increasing awareness and unprecedented progressive tendency. While traditional individuals persist and resist thoughts beyond their teachings, this segment might not be significant enough to sway the whole. Among Christians, historical awareness will grow significantly in the coming years. A longing will spread to distinguish the doctrines added to Christianity over time from the original intent of its namesake. This might take decades or even centuries, but the result is inevitable: a significant reversal in Christian history's trend towards its original form. A movement will grow, peeling away layers of doctrine one by one, as if time were moving backward, until only the concept introduced by Jesus on God's behalf remains, prior to other thinkers' claims. When this trend spreads across the United States and Europe, inspiring masses to worship as if living in Jesus' time, following only his ideas, the church will remain strong to guide the way. However, as the theological clock rewinds, the extreme diversity in Christianity will consolidate into more uniform beliefs and practices. Between regions, denominations, and divisions of all kinds, we will see increasing similarities instead of differences. Human history is filled with great reversions. One example is how Christians were once persecuted by the Roman Empire, but later that empire became a Christian institution. Our nation has transitioned from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The coming great reversion will unfold in the Christian religion, undoing history in search of its source and reducing diversity in the process. It is vital to recognize that this process will be enabled by interpreting Jesus' words metaphorically, rather than as literal statements. So, what has happened since Jesus' lifetime? Looking back far enough in history, we find only Judaism, the theological foundation of Christianity. By the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E., monotheism, the perception of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were central to the religion. The Jewish people did not share a single spirit; they were divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common people.

I believe that "The Jungle" illustrates how humans are inherently greedy and self-centered. They only care about their own interests and try to make their lives as good as possible, without considering those below them. The book reveals this through various ways, notably through the owners and managers of large factories. Their only concern is to make their companies and factories as big and powerful as possible. They disregard anything or anyone that stands in their way or is harmed by their progress. According to Upton Sinclair's work, "The outlines of the buildings stood clear against the sky; here and there rose great chimneys, with rivers of smoke trailing off to the world's end." Sinclair attempts to depict the huge damage caused by this pollution. He shows that the owners have no regard for people or animals that might be harmed. They do not care about the huge plumes of smoke from the factories or the runoff of animal waste from the thousands of pens around Packingtown.

The owners and managers also disregard the employees who make them rich. They would do anything to earn or save an extra dollar, "So from top to bottom, the place is simply a boiling pot of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere, and a man counts for nothing against a dollar." They force employees to work long hours and then, without notice, lay off large numbers of people without compensation or help finding new jobs. During the era "The Jungle" is set in, there were few, if any, laws or regulations protecting workers' safety and well-being. This allowed managers and owners to act freely, forcing employees to speed up work and endure terrible conditions. Although the book does not directly state it, those living and working themselves to death in Packingtown were expected to endure these horrible conditions both at work and at home. There were no agencies or organizations to provide information or assistance to workers. There were unions, but they often did more harm than good by profiting from the poor workers. The workers were treated so badly and had no escape from the Packingtown system that they were likened to slaves, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, always on the brink of starvation and dependent on the whims of men as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is just as inevitable and prevalent as under chattel slavery."

Edgar Allan Poe's "Dream-Land" is considered one of his finer poems. In this work, Poe uses the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott traces back to Virgil. Virgil referred to an island north of Britain, seen by the Greeks as the edge of the known world. While Virgil's usage is certain, there is a more recent influence worth noting. Poe had a keen interest in German authors. This quote is significant as it reveals Poe's familiarity with Goethe's writings. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe’s Politian and Goethe’s Mignon," comments on how similar their poems are, suggesting Poe imitated Goethe.

The "Oxford Companion to English Literature" notes that Goethe was a renowned author of the poetic drama "Faust," published in two parts in 1808 and 1832, the year of Goethe's death. Within the second part of "Faust" is a short poem titled "The King of Thulé." This poem narrates the story of a king who, after his wife's death, drinks heavily from the goblet she gifted him. Overcome with grief, he decides to die, relinquishing his possessions to his children except for the goblet. He throws it into the sea from a cliff, closes his eyes, and dies. The king’s demeanor and the portrayal of the king in "Dream-Land" are quite similar, perhaps reflecting Poe's own struggles with loss and alcohol. "Faust" was also adapted into a romantic drama by H P Grattan in 1842, just a year before Poe used "Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum."

Poe references Thule twice in his collected works. He mentions "Ultma Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and uses the term twice in "Dream-Land," marking the beginning and end of the poem. "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" can thus be seen as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes Thule as dark, lonely, haunted by dead friends, and colorless, which mirrors Goethe's "The King of Thulé" as he mourns his wife, feels isolated, and loses his will to live or rule. The poem reads as if the speaker has stepped into Goethe's work.

Goethe was a significant author, and Poe would have known of him, if only through his respect for Tennyson. When asked if he admired Tennyson, Poe had certain opinions. Besides his connection to Tennyson, Poe would have encountered Goethe's works through the many reproductions that followed the original publications.

Under California law, could a customer injured after slipping on spilled applesauce in a grocery store be awarded punitive damages by proving the store manager acted maliciously because he was informed twice about the spill and failed to clean it for half an hour due to having dinner?

A judge is unlikely to immediately dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages. To justify such an award, the plaintiff must show evidence that the defendant acted with a willful and conscious disregard for likely harm and that the conduct was despicable. Palmer could argue that Martin should have known the likely harm of not cleaning a spill because multiple D&D customers had been injured from slipping in the months prior; despite this, he still failed to clean it. Palmer's argument that Martin's actions were despicable is less convincing but still reasonable, given that six slip-and-fall incidents occurred in 2009 and Martin failed to take proper actions to ensure store safety.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, D&D Markets employee Rich Wayne informed his manager, Paul Martin, of an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin told Wayne he was on dinner break and "didn't have time to deal with customer complaints." At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also informed Mr. Martin of the spill, and Martin responded the same way. At 5:30 pm on the 13th, the plaintiff, Jennifer Palmer, slipped on the spill and suffered a serious back injury. Before Palmer's accident, five different slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D's in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages related to her injury, and we are considering whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damage claim.

In California, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of a non-contractual obligation if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud or malice." Cal. Civ. Code § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct intended to cause harm, or in the absence of intent, the conduct must be "despicable" and carried out with "a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." Courts describe conduct as malicious when it is done with conscious disregard of the plaintiff's rights, meaning the defendant "was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his conduct and willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences." Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

She always felt she needed something, a desire that never seemed to be fulfilled. This feeling began when she was 14, just stepping into her teenage years. Even at 17, it persisted. She realized she wanted someone rather than something, yet no boys caught her interest. Some tried to win her over, but none attracted her. She often questioned this strange feeling, wondering what could cause such a situation for a teenage girl. Years of contemplation led to theories, but none compelling enough to ponder deeply. So she continued her life, questioning her desires.

A day at home was usually peaceful. Her parents were kind and calm, rarely arguing with each other or with her. The only topic of contention was her assertion of independence and free spirit. Although she was the daughter of a calm couple, her vibrant and fun personality contrasted with their energies, making her likable, as she was a nice person.

Today, however, was not a calm day. As she moved from room to room, seeking new inspiration, she heard a short scream from the kitchen, her mother's beautiful voice. She rushed in, panicked, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She saw her mother on the floor, in pain, repeatedly saying "Ow" between breaths. The daughter ran to her, trying to help. "Ouch... sweetie, I... need you to take me to... the hospital." Her words were rushed and strained, and her daughter knew she was in severe pain. "Okay, Mom, just tell me how to get you there." Her mother guided her, and at that moment, she was grateful for her strength training. She carried her mother to the car, laid her in the back seat, and drove.

The hospital visit was filled with the smell of disinfectant and sickness, tinged with fear. But she didn't notice, her mind focused on helping her mother. She quickly brought her injured mother in and called for doctors. Worried faces gathered, and someone brought a rolling bed to lay her mother down. They took her for immediate examination, leaving her daughter to worry.

Her mother had fallen off a step stool while trying to reach a vase from the highest cabinet.

This study aimed to demonstrate that following a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," is associated with a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as stroke mortality. The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet, characterized by higher consumption of plant-based foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (compared to saturated fats), and fish, while reducing the intake of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is allowed.

Previous prospective studies have documented an inverse relationship between adherence to a Med diet and total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality. An intervention trial showed that the Med diet was more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and reducing the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals. Previous studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women aged 38 to 63, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states. From 1984 to 2004, the authors calculated an aMed diet score six times from self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake over the previous year. More than 95% of the nurses continued participation throughout the 20-year period. FFQs underwent validation studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed through reviews of medical or hospital records, autopsies, or death certificates. Where records were unavailable, cases were considered "probable" and included, with about 17% of strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarctions classified as such. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and use of postmenopausal hormone were calculated for each FFQ, and starting in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed.

To reduce random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging scores from two prior years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" (factors that could confuse results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to evaluate the association between an aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women. Over the 20-year follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were identified. Women in the highest aMed quintile had a lower risk of both CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

Hitler is alive in Burma, the sign declares.

Ellen Page, star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner, holding up a piece of cardboard with an unsettling message written in Sharpie. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian country ruled by a tyrannical military junta that came to power in a 1962 coup. In 2007, a series of street protests erupted, marking the first public demonstrations in a decade. Led by numerous Burmese monks, these protests became known as the "Saffron Revolution," named after the color of the monks' robes. After the initial uprisings, the public began to take interest in the protests. Although the Burmese government initially allowed the monks to gather peacefully, violence soon escalated into what some saw as an all-out war between the monks and the military junta, with the military invading and looting monasteries nationwide. Foreign journalists were detained and imprisoned, and a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai was killed on September 27, 2007, simply for attending a street protest. While the official death toll was reported as 13, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army days before the official report, claimed, "Many more people have been killed in recent days than you’ve heard about. The bodies can be counted in several thousand."

This is nothing new. While these are some of the most recent examples of atrocities in our world, the desire of governments to suppress dissent and maintain complete control over their citizens has existed since the dawn of civilization. Early Roman emperors declared themselves chosen by the gods to wield complete executive power over every aspect of their society. Japanese emperors are believed to be actual gods, sent to our world to lead their people to prosperity through inventions like Motorola cell phones and the practice of hara-kiri. Our current president, George W. Bush, reportedly holds weekly calls with Ted Haggard, leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary of the Republican Party.

Some of the most well-known examples of such actions include the June 4, 1989, protest at Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students gathered to protest the government's authoritarian rule. The death toll from that event varies widely, with Chinese government reports citing 200-300 dead, while the Chinese Red Cross reports 2,000-3,000 dead. Another example is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, with government support, began systematically killing all Tutsis and political moderates regardless of ethnic background. Hitler’s 'Third Reich' is another extreme example, spanning several years and countries, where anyone of Jewish background was rounded up and killed.

Duke Ellington's legacy in jazz is largely attributed to his longevity, which allowed him to demonstrate his creative abilities in shaping his orchestra. His presence on the piano in many of the compositions selected for this assignment is subtle, but as a composer, Ellington excelled in creating rich and complex pieces that highlighted the individual talents of band members. He crafted a framework where soloists could freely improvise, while also writing tightly orchestrated pieces and phrases that utilized the unique styles of band members to emphasize musical ideas. In doing so, he accentuated the orchestra's tone more broadly, creating coherent and original sounds for each piece. Ellington's mastery of the individual players' sounds and their integration within an evolving ensemble enabled him to compose some of the most innovative and brilliant works in jazz history.

The Grove Music Dictionary, in discussing Ellington's sound and innovation, references "Creole Love Call" as an example of using the voice "as a jazz instrument" throughout his career. This is an early instance of Ellington using the voice to add texture and color without lyrics. "Creole Love Call" also demonstrates Ellington's ability to complement his soloists' styles, evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues piece contains six choruses, as follows:
Chorus 1: A call and response between voice and reeds, starting smooth and melodic, then transitioning to a rougher sound towards the end.
Chorus 2: A muted trumpet solo elaborating on the basic melody and emphasizing several extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: A sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, backed by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
Chorus 4: The full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response by the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic section of the piece, with reeds beginning the call and response in a high register, supported by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with a call and response between voice and reeds. In this chorus, the voice uses the "growl" technique, soloing as an instrument.
Tag: A brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.

Ellington's use of voice to add a dimension of tone color in this piece exemplifies a stylistic trait that permeates his work. In "Hot and Bothered," recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill in tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response phrase between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing uses the vocal elements of Miley's playing and the instrumental aspects of Cox's voice to create a rich and complementary sound. "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)" extends these ideas, with Ellington using Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton, a mainstay in Ellington's orchestra, to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

Why do organisms evolve in the way they do? Are there any limitations or constraints that affect the direction of evolutionary changes? Even though D’Arcy Thompson mentioned in 1917 that "even now, the zoologist has hardly begun to dream of defining even the simplest organic forms in mathematical language," this statement still holds today. Recently, mathematical modeling has been applied to study general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through ontogeny and phylogeny (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our research is exploring how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, combined with experimental studies, can be used to clarify the mechanisms involved in the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental changes. We used X-ray images of Prunum species to define quantitative parameters that could be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were entered into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies to interpret the boundaries of possible morphological changes in Prunum. These results are being combined with experimental and descriptive studies to better understand macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be regarded as a structure that is a tube traveling through 360 degrees of space over time. These revolutions or turns of a coiled shell are called whorls, which are considered to spiral around an imaginary central axis. This axis runs through the central column of the shell and is known as the columella. The rate at which the whorls enlarge can vary, and a continuous line separates each whorl, known as a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl is the last one (body whorl). The spire includes all whorls except the last one. The apex is the tip of the spire, and the opposite end is referred to as the base. The animal extends out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be observed in apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural views. (The "usual" orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing up.)

Below is a method for counting whorls. First, the shell should be viewed from the apical view, and then determine where the first suture begins. A line can then be drawn dividing the shell into two parts. Whorls are counted from this line and are estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of apertures that travel through time and space as the animal accretes (i.e., builds) its shell. It is possible to trace the path of the aperture via the coordinates of the center of each whorl’s aperture as well as the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented. Once a mathematical formulation is established, it is possible to vary parameters and modify the mollusk’s skeletogenesis.

The rate of neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia has stayed quite constant over the past ten years. Although the country is progressing towards several Millennium Development Goals, such as water and sanitation, the improvements in child and maternal health are far from sufficient to meet the 2015 targets. The reasons for these shortcomings will be discussed below, indicating a need to strengthen the health system rather than focusing solely on programmatic interventions.

Indonesia has improved in the number of births attended by skilled health workers, with 72% now meeting this criterion. However, this figure still includes traditional workers like midwives, who may not provide medical interventions in complicated pregnancies, leading to many maternal deaths from hemorrhage. Therefore, the improvements in this particular indicator are somewhat misleading, showing that much work remains. Additionally, there has been a decline in the percentage of diarrheal cases in children under five treated by health professionals. Although postnatal care data is incomplete, it is clear that this area is also concerning, with low rates nationwide.

Cesarean section rates are still lower than expected, around 4%. This rate additionally highlights another issue: while the c-section rate is 7% in urban areas, it is only 2% in rural areas, pointing to the problem of equity in healthcare coverage across the country. Clearly, access to healthcare services is concentrated in urban areas. Another access issue concerns vertical equity, with a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles. The poor evidently face more difficulties accessing healthcare services, likely due to out-of-pocket costs.

In discussing next steps for improving neonatal and maternal care indicators, the fundamental question is how to effectively address the service shortfall. Specifically, should Indonesia develop program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system without focusing on pre and post-pregnancy care for mothers and children? While programmatic approaches to solving the problems outlined above are attractive, as "vertical approaches" targeting specific sectors have more focused, manageable objectives and often yield quicker results, there are drawbacks. One major drawback is that investing heavily in one area often means other areas suffer from a lack of funding, with human resources drawn to the better-resourced area, as seen with international funding for HIV/AIDS affecting the family planning sector. Additionally, running multiple parallel programs in one area leads to service duplication and lack of coordination, increasing forms and paperwork for supplies and funding.

The classification of popular music has expanded over the past century to encompass so many genres that it is difficult to list them all comprehensively. Further complicating matters, nearly all genres—such as rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk—have generated various sub-genres and sub-sub-genres. Heavy metal rock, in particular, has arguably become one of the most diverse and expressive genres in popular music over the last 40 years. It is expressive because it explores a wide range of emotions, often leaning towards darker themes. It is diverse because, soon after its emergence, people recognized its flexibility and began creating their own sub-genres, followed by further sub-sub-genres, a trend that continues today.

Currently, the heavy metal movement has evolved to a point where there are so many niche groups that it is challenging to define what heavy metal truly is. It has absorbed numerous themes from other genres, yet like everything else, it originated somewhere. To truly understand the metal music prevalent today, one must first comprehend what the metal movement is and why it is considered a movement rather than merely a genre.

Metal, in many ways, is a movement characterized by darkness. It is often seen as "music of more"—more bass, more volume, more intensity, and more theatricality. Less primitive, more skilled; musicians in metal bands are adept with their instruments, and this proficiency is evident in their music. Metal is also significantly influenced by drug use, particularly during the psychedelic drug boom of the mid-70s, leading to the creation of wild and otherworldly records, using drugs as a catalyst. It possesses many dark, visceral qualities, which were novel to the music scene since much of popular music did not delve into the darker emotional spectrum. Later generations of metal have drawn influence from these dark, visceral qualities, reminiscent of those present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics like those from Helter Skelter illustrate the darkness central to the movement.

The lyrics from Helter Skelter showcase the Beatles' darker side, depicting the ups and downs, supposedly related to drug experiences. This song is considered by some as one of the first heavy metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also heavier and darker. The Beatles aimed to demonstrate they could be as heavy as the Stones, which is why they included it on The White Album.

Several decades before Surrealist artists started creating their dreamlike works, artist Henri Rousseau was meticulously shaping his own dreams, both literally and metaphorically. The 1910 painting "The Dream" by the renowned Post-Impressionist artist not only depicts a woman marveling at the wonders of a land she visits in a dream but also represents Rousseau’s personal dreams and aspirations as a painter. Since he began his work, he dreamed of gaining recognition, acceptance, and praise from other artists and art lovers but found himself facing a challenging internal conflict to achieve this goal. "The Dream" is the work of Henri Rousseau that best reflects his lifelong internal struggle: whether to conform to or imitate certain painting styles to be accepted by the critical art world he dearly loved or to allow himself creative independence and uniqueness, forging his own path. Before analyzing "The Dream" from this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biography. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who enjoyed "bourgeois prosperity" (Shattuck 47). Growing up, Rousseau received no formal art training; instead, he worked for the French government as a municipal toll service employee until the age of forty, although he was mistakenly called a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, after the loss of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). Thus, he sought refuge in a new life and turned to painting for comfort and a fresh start. Unlike his contemporaries who sentimentalized and romanticized peasants in their art, Rousseau was essentially a folk painter, with the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class. Rousseau's obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable in context: as noted, he was not only uneducated in formal painting methods and began his career at a later age but was also creating works alongside many other talented and better-known modern artists. Despite working for many years, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse was establishing his reputation as an artist. In the book "Modern French Painters," author Jan Gordon asserts that while the two were technically competitors in the art world, they differed not only in style and subject matter but also in their reasons for painting: "Matisse was a painter who feared painting in a trite way, while Rousseau's desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français" (92).

Many great thinkers have suggested a close connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe there is a fundamental reason for this. As John Keats states in "Ode on a Grecian Urn," "Beauty is truth, truth beauty—that is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." Much of what we learn in life comes from education or experience. However, as Keats implies, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics without being taught in the conventional sense. Both ethics and aesthetics aim to describe, not prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty largely try to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than setting rules for judging or creating good art or moral behavior.

Moreover, criticism of art or morals never fully captures the essence of what is good or beautiful. For instance, discussions about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa might focus on concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but ultimately, these do not explain why it is great art. Instead, when asked about a favorite work of art or literature, people often say, "There's just something about it," before offering more complex or critical explanations. I believe that art and morals can never be completely reduced to descriptions of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way... you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." No matter how thoroughly we describe the properties of a work of literature, something transcendent remains. I believe ethics shares this characteristic. As Wittgenstein notes, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental." I propose that this "something," this indefinable quality, is the most powerful attribute of art and morality, and that this transcendental nature provides a connection point between ethics and aesthetics.

I believe morality and art are closely linked because we experience them most profoundly at a noumenal level, to use a Kantian term. They affect us in ways that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is especially strong in the art of literature. As McKean says, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. Moral standards may be inappropriate for other arts, like music, but they seem as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values... Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

Today's Germany is seen as a powerful and united nation, with a culture that blends elements from the shadow of the Alps in Munich to the Baltic city of Kiel. This culture is evident from Cologne on the Rhine, through the center of Germany, to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it is no surprise that modern Germany has roots in various sources and tribes.

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans, and the origin of its name is a subject of much debate among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic tribe known as the Tungrians, who were called Germans before they crossed the Rhine and fought the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98 AD). Julius Caesar first used the term "Germanus" in his commentary on the Gallic Wars, where he subdued the Gauls and battled Germanic tribes that often crossed the Rhine under dubious pretenses. He borrowed this word from the Gauls themselves to distinguish those he had conquered (the Gauls) from those he had not. Although the origin is uncertain, some suggest it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar noted: "Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (the Gauls) are continually waging war... They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles." (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim, meaning "to shout," indicating that Germans were loud or noisy. (Names of Germany)

Early Roman historian Tacitus, in his AD 98 work "De Origine et situ Germanorum," recorded the origins of the Germans, writing: "I should regard (the Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times, it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive... Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?" (Tacitus, 98 AD)

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, at least not yet. They would send their conquerors into the lands of Germania for goods, and occasionally launch land campaigns, but in the end, they mostly returned home to their vast empire. So, when the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire, trading goods taken from the land and showcasing their skills by serving in the Roman army. (Ozment, 2005, p. 17)

The play "Twelfth Night" suggests that although disguises are indeed useful for long-term deception, ultimately, one must reject the new facade to avoid losing themselves forever. However, a major issue with ending the deception is the risk of alienation. Therefore, one must choose between self-preservation and maintaining relationships with others, as some may react neutrally to being deceived, while others may take offense at the entire charade.

The theme of deception in gender role reversal is particularly problematic, raising many side issues, notably, why? Why does a person feel the need to abandon their identity and disguise themselves as the opposite gender? In Viola's case, it is clearly a form of self-protection: "I'll bring you to a captain in this town / Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help / I was preserved to serve this noble count..." (5.1.247-249).

Upon arriving in a foreign land, Viola finds it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from potential attackers. Her plan works but alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from a vital support system. Worse, she's so convincing as a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian and falls in love with her. "Where, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay." (5.1.138) Additionally, she also has to contend with suppressed romantic feelings between her and Orsino: "Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times / Thou never shouldst love woman like to me." (5.1.260-261).

While this might be seen as a progressive attitude, to modern readers, "Twelfth Night" illustrates how deception can facilitate the revelation of suppressed emotions, particularly for Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages suggest these characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that Viola/Cesario's presence forces them to confront. For example, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because he appears to be a man, or does she secretly harbor feelings for women? It's arguable that this is not the case, as Shakespeare's character Olivia likely parodies those from his era who judge others solely on appearances.

This is evidenced by Olivia's ease in shifting her romantic interest from Cesario to Sebastian, and subsequently regarding Cesario/Viola as family rather than a romantic interest: "A sister, you are she." (5.1.315).

German colonial rule was noted by many observers for its brutality, especially concerning the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Naturally, something as broad as an entire colonial empire cannot be summed up by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was diverse in its policies and ruling styles, much like its geographical spread. Educational provision in the colonies was equally varied. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large number of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors.

The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) was in stark contrast.
