Indonesia has improved in the number of births attended by skilled health workers, with 72% now meeting this criterion. However, this figure still includes traditional workers like midwives, who may not provide medical interventions in complicated pregnancies, leading to many maternal deaths from hemorrhage. Therefore, the improvements in this particular indicator are somewhat misleading, showing that much work remains. Additionally, there has been a decline in the percentage of diarrheal cases in children under five treated by health professionals. Although postnatal care data is incomplete, it is clear that this area is also concerning, with low rates nationwide.

Cesarean section rates are still lower than expected, around 4%. This rate additionally highlights another issue: while the c-section rate is 7% in urban areas, it is only 2% in rural areas, pointing to the problem of equity in healthcare coverage across the country. Clearly, access to healthcare services is concentrated in urban areas. Another access issue concerns vertical equity, with a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles. The poor evidently face more difficulties accessing healthcare services, likely due to out-of-pocket costs.

In discussing next steps for improving neonatal and maternal care indicators, the fundamental question is how to effectively address the service shortfall. Specifically, should Indonesia develop program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system without focusing on pre and post-pregnancy care for mothers and children? While programmatic approaches to solving the problems outlined above are attractive, as "vertical approaches" targeting specific sectors have more focused, manageable objectives and often yield quicker results, there are drawbacks. One major drawback is that investing heavily in one area often means other areas suffer from a lack of funding, with human resources drawn to the better-resourced area, as seen with international funding for HIV/AIDS affecting the family planning sector. Additionally, running multiple parallel programs in one area leads to service duplication and lack of coordination, increasing forms and paperwork for supplies and funding.

The classification of popular music has expanded over the past century to encompass so many genres that it is difficult to list them all comprehensively. Further complicating matters, nearly all genres—such as rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk—have generated various sub-genres and sub-sub-genres. Heavy metal rock, in particular, has arguably become one of the most diverse and expressive genres in popular music over the last 40 years. It is expressive because it explores a wide range of emotions, often leaning towards darker themes. It is diverse because, soon after its emergence, people recognized its flexibility and began creating their own sub-genres, followed by further sub-sub-genres, a trend that continues today.

Currently, the heavy metal movement has evolved to a point where there are so many niche groups that it is challenging to define what heavy metal truly is. It has absorbed numerous themes from other genres, yet like everything else, it originated somewhere. To truly understand the metal music prevalent today, one must first comprehend what the metal movement is and why it is considered a movement rather than merely a genre.

Metal, in many ways, is a movement characterized by darkness. It is often seen as "music of more"—more bass, more volume, more intensity, and more theatricality. Less primitive, more skilled; musicians in metal bands are adept with their instruments, and this proficiency is evident in their music. Metal is also significantly influenced by drug use, particularly during the psychedelic drug boom of the mid-70s, leading to the creation of wild and otherworldly records, using drugs as a catalyst. It possesses many dark, visceral qualities, which were novel to the music scene since much of popular music did not delve into the darker emotional spectrum. Later generations of metal have drawn influence from these dark, visceral qualities, reminiscent of those present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics like those from Helter Skelter illustrate the darkness central to the movement.

The lyrics from Helter Skelter showcase the Beatles' darker side, depicting the ups and downs, supposedly related to drug experiences. This song is considered by some as one of the first heavy metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also heavier and darker. The Beatles aimed to demonstrate they could be as heavy as the Stones, which is why they included it on The White Album.

Several decades before Surrealist artists started creating their dreamlike works, artist Henri Rousseau was meticulously shaping his own dreams, both literally and metaphorically. The 1910 painting "The Dream" by the renowned Post-Impressionist artist not only depicts a woman marveling at the wonders of a land she visits in a dream but also represents Rousseau’s personal dreams and aspirations as a painter. Since he began his work, he dreamed of gaining recognition, acceptance, and praise from other artists and art lovers but found himself facing a challenging internal conflict to achieve this goal. "The Dream" is the work of Henri Rousseau that best reflects his lifelong internal struggle: whether to conform to or imitate certain painting styles to be accepted by the critical art world he dearly loved or to allow himself creative independence and uniqueness, forging his own path. Before analyzing "The Dream" from this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biography. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who enjoyed "bourgeois prosperity" (Shattuck 47). Growing up, Rousseau received no formal art training; instead, he worked for the French government as a municipal toll service employee until the age of forty, although he was mistakenly called a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, after the loss of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). Thus, he sought refuge in a new life and turned to painting for comfort and a fresh start. Unlike his contemporaries who sentimentalized and romanticized peasants in their art, Rousseau was essentially a folk painter, with the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class. Rousseau's obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable in context: as noted, he was not only uneducated in formal painting methods and began his career at a later age but was also creating works alongside many other talented and better-known modern artists. Despite working for many years, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse was establishing his reputation as an artist. In the book "Modern French Painters," author Jan Gordon asserts that while the two were technically competitors in the art world, they differed not only in style and subject matter but also in their reasons for painting: "Matisse was a painter who feared painting in a trite way, while Rousseau's desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français" (92).

Many great thinkers have suggested a close connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe there is a fundamental reason for this. As John Keats states in "Ode on a Grecian Urn," "Beauty is truth, truth beauty—that is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." Much of what we learn in life comes from education or experience. However, as Keats implies, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics without being taught in the conventional sense. Both ethics and aesthetics aim to describe, not prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty largely try to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than setting rules for judging or creating good art or moral behavior.

Moreover, criticism of art or morals never fully captures the essence of what is good or beautiful. For instance, discussions about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa might focus on concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but ultimately, these do not explain why it is great art. Instead, when asked about a favorite work of art or literature, people often say, "There's just something about it," before offering more complex or critical explanations. I believe that art and morals can never be completely reduced to descriptions of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way... you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." No matter how thoroughly we describe the properties of a work of literature, something transcendent remains. I believe ethics shares this characteristic. As Wittgenstein notes, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental." I propose that this "something," this indefinable quality, is the most powerful attribute of art and morality, and that this transcendental nature provides a connection point between ethics and aesthetics.

I believe morality and art are closely linked because we experience them most profoundly at a noumenal level, to use a Kantian term. They affect us in ways that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is especially strong in the art of literature. As McKean says, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. Moral standards may be inappropriate for other arts, like music, but they seem as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values... Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

Today's Germany is seen as a powerful and united nation, with a culture that blends elements from the shadow of the Alps in Munich to the Baltic city of Kiel. This culture is evident from Cologne on the Rhine, through the center of Germany, to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it is no surprise that modern Germany has roots in various sources and tribes.

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans, and the origin of its name is a subject of much debate among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic tribe known as the Tungrians, who were called Germans before they crossed the Rhine and fought the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98 AD). Julius Caesar first used the term "Germanus" in his commentary on the Gallic Wars, where he subdued the Gauls and battled Germanic tribes that often crossed the Rhine under dubious pretenses. He borrowed this word from the Gauls themselves to distinguish those he had conquered (the Gauls) from those he had not. Although the origin is uncertain, some suggest it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar noted: "Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (the Gauls) are continually waging war... They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles." (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim, meaning "to shout," indicating that Germans were loud or noisy. (Names of Germany)

Early Roman historian Tacitus, in his AD 98 work "De Origine et situ Germanorum," recorded the origins of the Germans, writing: "I should regard (the Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times, it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive... Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?" (Tacitus, 98 AD)

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, at least not yet. They would send their conquerors into the lands of Germania for goods, and occasionally launch land campaigns, but in the end, they mostly returned home to their vast empire. So, when the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire, trading goods taken from the land and showcasing their skills by serving in the Roman army. (Ozment, 2005, p. 17)

The play "Twelfth Night" suggests that although disguises are indeed useful for long-term deception, ultimately, one must reject the new facade to avoid losing themselves forever. However, a major issue with ending the deception is the risk of alienation. Therefore, one must choose between self-preservation and maintaining relationships with others, as some may react neutrally to being deceived, while others may take offense at the entire charade.

The theme of deception in gender role reversal is particularly problematic, raising many side issues, notably, why? Why does a person feel the need to abandon their identity and disguise themselves as the opposite gender? In Viola's case, it is clearly a form of self-protection: "I'll bring you to a captain in this town / Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help / I was preserved to serve this noble count..." (5.1.247-249).

Upon arriving in a foreign land, Viola finds it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from potential attackers. Her plan works but alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from a vital support system. Worse, she's so convincing as a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian and falls in love with her. "Where, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay." (5.1.138) Additionally, she also has to contend with suppressed romantic feelings between her and Orsino: "Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times / Thou never shouldst love woman like to me." (5.1.260-261).

While this might be seen as a progressive attitude, to modern readers, "Twelfth Night" illustrates how deception can facilitate the revelation of suppressed emotions, particularly for Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages suggest these characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that Viola/Cesario's presence forces them to confront. For example, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because he appears to be a man, or does she secretly harbor feelings for women? It's arguable that this is not the case, as Shakespeare's character Olivia likely parodies those from his era who judge others solely on appearances.

This is evidenced by Olivia's ease in shifting her romantic interest from Cesario to Sebastian, and subsequently regarding Cesario/Viola as family rather than a romantic interest: "A sister, you are she." (5.1.315).

German colonial rule was noted by many observers for its brutality, especially concerning the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Naturally, something as broad as an entire colonial empire cannot be summed up by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was diverse in its policies and ruling styles, much like its geographical spread. Educational provision in the colonies was equally varied. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large number of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors.

The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) was in stark contrast. Unlike in East Africa, where the government had established state schools and played a significant role in native education, in South West Africa, the task of educating the natives was almost entirely left to missionary societies with limited government support. However, the government did invest significant resources in the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing a system of state schools and providing more support and regulation for missionary schools. These educational policies had long-lasting effects on South West Africa, even after German rule ended. While other German colonies had significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa, "the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate." Various social, political, and economic factors contributed to the different experiences in South West Africa. This paper aims to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and focusing on new research regarding the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities towards native Africans.

There is a wealth of literature specifically addressing education in the German colonial empire. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies highlighted significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work explicitly addressing the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors accounting for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinctive aspects of the colony’s educational system.

Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population in South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The United States and Mexico once experienced a rivalry that lasted 57 years, from 1836 to 1893, as noted by Diehl and Goerts (2000, p. 145). The peak of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, during which the United States attacked and defeated Mexico, gaining Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. Many other conflicts arose between the two nations, subsiding just before World War I. The rivalry started with clashes over key issues like religion, culture, and tradition, as well as significant material interests (Schmitt 1974, p. 30-31).

This situation is similar to many other nations that have long-standing rivalries with their neighbors. Countries sharing a border often face conflicts of interest, leading to rival positions. The rivalry between the United States and Mexico is akin to many other enduring rivalries between nations with shared borders. David M. Pletcher (1977) states, "Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems" (p. 41). Indeed, both these nations are geographically close to the United States and have been its rivals, unlike other Latin American countries that have enjoyed good relations with the United States.

Religious issues created a rift between the two countries, a problem that has troubled many nations throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) notes that "if in the twentieth century Americans opposed fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries they opposed Catholicism and monarchy" (p. 86). Similar to the Cold War rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union, which was part ideological struggle and part a competition over vital interests, this case, however, focused on religious preferences rather than political structures. This distrust was rooted in the historical animosity between the English and Spanish. Inheriting this distrust from their colonial rulers was a major barrier to establishing amicable foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during the 57-year rivalry. Most disputes described by Diehl and Goerts involved territorial issues related to border raids from Mexican territory into the U.S. and other frontier problems. Border raids by bandits and outlaws were a significant issue until both the United States and Mexico exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974, p. 97).

Schmitt (1974) explains that the rivalry between the two nations began to diminish as "Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way" (p. 109), and finally ended as American objectives shifted "from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico" (p. 110) in the later part of the 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, an illness I had never heard of suddenly left me disabled.

At that time, I was a nurse. I chose this profession because of a deep-seated need for the safety and security I lacked as a child. Growing up, I often heard the saying, "You'll always be able to find work because people will always get sick." Despite my dream of becoming a scientist or a journalist, or ideally both, I chose nursing.

However, there I was, 46 years old, single, with barely any money in the bank and unable to work. To this day, I remain disabled, and after 15 years of living on Social Security Disability, I have virtually nothing left that I can call "mine." I get by, but each day is a challenge to my security, safety, and self-esteem. There's nothing certain in my life anymore, but one thing I know for sure: without the help of my family and a few good friends, I could not have made it through all these years, no matter how strong I was. And believe me, when real disaster strikes, you don't feel strong at all.

My point is that emergencies, big and small, are a constant in life. There are no guarantees, and no matter how well-prepared you are, some things are just too big to handle alone.

I fully agree that we in the U.S. should stop putting all our hopes in the "basket" of big government; it's moldy and falling apart. However, I would much rather see Americans learning to trust each other again—learning to help one another and to ask for help, rather than each of us individually rushing to build fallout shelters.

Conservatives in the U.S. talk about the "rugged individualism" that built this country, but in reality, what kept our forefathers going during tough times wasn't rugged individualism; it was compassion, mutual respect, and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone.

So by all means, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit with first aid supplies, water purification tablets, and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in case of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all sorts of batteries, plenty of candles, waterproof matches, and canned goods. If you have the land and resources for a small farm and can preserve your own food, do it. It's a great idea, as is a wood stove, as long as you don't live in an apartment.

But while you're at it, get to know your neighbors.

Somewhere around the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince was born who would later be known as Buddha. Throughout his life, he abandoned worldly life and achieved enlightenment, and his teachings led to the establishment of Buddhism, with its most orthodox sect being Theravada Buddhism. This religion is about two and a half millennia old; it appears different today compared to when Buddha was alive. This change is evident globally, such as in the Theravada Buddhist nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Both monks and laypeople participate in this ceremony, which holds some religious significance, despite Buddha not having taught any such festival. These differences range from superficial traditions to the core of the religion's salvation beliefs. The Theravada Buddhist community, from both the monastic and lay perspectives, has had to alter its doctrinal principles over time. This can be attributed to forces both internal and external, both hostile and benign.

There are several qualifying terms that will be frequently used in this discussion. One such concept is internal versus external. Here, an internal force is defined as a force arising from members of the Buddhist community, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any force from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that harms or intends to harm the Buddhist community, stemming from a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is one that does not intend to harm or help the Buddhist community, though it may inadvertently do one or the other. These terms will recur throughout the discussion.

Firstly, it is important to examine the fundamentals of the religion—the doctrines that are at the heart of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially comprised of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist scriptures. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical components of Buddhism. These metaphysical notions include concepts like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—the inherent suffering in life, and Anicca—the impermanence of everything. Only by recognizing these concepts can one end Samsara, the continuous cycle of death and rebirth. Along with Samsara, lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, will cease when one becomes enlightened. In the Vinaya Pitaka, rules for life are set forth. For laypeople, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to follow. The most fundamental doctrinal notion in Buddhism is the concept of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.
